{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef0ce363-65af-4561-8ddf-dd139a58ba37","content":"Since you want consistency across all 3 projects, use a shared `Directory.Build.props` at the solution level rather than editing each `.csproj`.\n\n**1. Create/update `Directory.Build.props` next to your `.sln`:**\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Opts into Microsoft.Testing.Platform instead of VSTest |\n| `OutputType` → `Exe` | MTP test projects must be executables |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Required on .NET 8 so `dotnet test` speaks the MTP protocol instead of VSTest |\n\n**2. Add the TRX extension to each test project** (or a `Directory.Packages.props` if using central package management):\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n```\n\nThe VSTest `--logger trx` flag doesn't exist in MTP — this package provides the equivalent.\n\n**3. Update your CI command:**\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` arguments from MTP arguments. `--report-trx` is provided by the TrxReport extension and writes `.trx` files to the `TestResults/` folder just like before.\n\n**That's it.** No changes needed to test code — `[TestClass]`, `[TestMethod]`, etc. all work identically under MTP.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84265a38-45d0-453d-9f48-5496a478c239","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate 3 MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). They're on .NET 8 SDK and use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer covering the required changes.\n\nKey changes for MSTest 3.8.0 on .NET 8:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each test project (or a shared `Directory.Build.props`).\n\n\n2. **TRX logger**: MSTest 3.8.0+ includes built-in TRX support through MTP, so the `dotnet test --logger trx` command should work as-is without additional packages, though you can optionally add `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` for more control over report generation. I'm realizing the distinction here—MSTest 3.8.0 with the traditional NuGet packages doesn't automatically include TRX support, so you'd need to add `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` separately even though the meta-package bundles the core components. The MSTest.Sdk approach is different and more comprehensive, but for existing projects using individual packages, the separate TRX extension is still required. I need to clarify the dependency chain here—`EnableMSTestRunner` pulls in `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` transitively through MSTest.TestAdapter, but the TRX reporting extension is a separate package that needs to be explicitly added. For .NET 8 specifically, `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is critical because without it, `dotnet test` falls back to VSTest protocol which isn't compatible with the Modern Testing Platform runner.","outputTokens":1518},"id":"46a396c8-8842-4a69-a879-ed024d720a50","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:42:08.455Z","parentId":"c5d02980-fc77-4395-84e5-a0d807f69b13"}
